A very active area of research, and one heavily adopted and refined in practice, relates to the use of search engine (i.e., information retrieval) technologies in order to enable Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) [DBLP:conf/nips/LewisPPPKGKLYR020,DBLP:conf/aaai/0011LH024]. This offers great potential for overcoming problems with non-factuality, staleness and bias in LLM responses, improving performance in particular for dynamic and long-tail factual queries.
 In the simplest RAG setting,
 documents relevant to a prompt are searched for at inference run-time and their content is injected into the context window of the LLM to improve 
 the generated responses.
 Recent AI assistants from big providers call a major SE to this end, but it is equally useful to inject in-house information for vertical domains, such as finance or health.
 More recent approaches
 advocate for Active 
 RAG
 [DBLP:conf/emnlp/JiangXGSLDYCN23], where relevant documents are iteratively retrieved during the generation process as needed, particularly when generating long texts. 
 RAG will 
 continue to be a very lively area, with various benchmarks gaining major attention
 (e.g., [DBLP:conf/aaai/0011LH024]).